### Rmd purposes

**Aim and context:**

This file is used to subset the ABARES NLUM dataset into relevant agricultural commodities and to plot their extent across Australia. This raster map is then overlaid with a shapefile of Australia to create a shapefiles of irrigation. Importantly, ABARES data has not necessarily correctly and fully assigned irrigated land, so this is instead mapped against Earth Observation irrigation data in the next Rmd file.

**Analysis:**

- Subset ABARES categories to agricultural cella at native 250m^2^ resolution
- Aggregate raster to 10 arc-min (\~324 km^2^) cells via `fun = "mean"`, to calculate a 0-1 proportion of agricultural land use at 250 m^2^
- Apply a 10% floor

**Outputs:** Density-graded map of the Australian agricultural plant zone, and shapefiles of agricultural production

**Palette:** hcl.colors(7, palette = "Purple-Yellow") \# "#80146E" "#7A55AB" "#478EC1" "#34B8C0" "#7ED5B8" "#C6E8BC" "#F5F2D8"

### Libraries and mapping setup

```{r setup, message=FALSE}
library(terra)      # rasters
library(tidyverse)  # data wrangling, %>%, select, distinct, arrange, mutate
library(ozmaps)     # australian mapping outlines
library(sf)         # needed by tidyterra
library(ggplot2)    # mapping
library(tidyterra)  # geom_spatraster, geom_spatvector
library(scales)     # map colours

terraOptions(progress = 0) # silent terra working
data("ozmap_states")      # get Australian state and territory boundaries
aus_states <- ozmap_states %>%
  filter(!NAME %in% c("Other Territories", "Jervis Bay Territory")) # call it aus_states, rm offshore islands
aus_states <- vect(aus_states)                       # define it as a vector
aus_states_albers <- project(aus_states, "EPSG:3577") # reproject to Australian Albers
```

### Data files

- Download and read in the most recent 2020-21 ABARES NLUM dataset from <https://www.agriculture.gov.au/abares/aclump/land-use/land-use-of-australia-2010-11-to-2020-21#downloads>

```{r data}
abares_csv <- read.csv("../data/NLUM_v7_250_INPUTS_2020_21_geo.csv") # read in csv
abares_tif <- rast("../data/NLUM_v7_250_INPUTS_2020_21_geo.tif")     # read in tif
```

### Subset ABARES categories to relevant land use types

- Category selection is based on the ABARES agricultural land use map, excluding animal agriculture (e.g. no grazing, hay and silage, intensive livestock farming etc.). The original map of agricultural commodities and the metadata on land use categories are available from ABARES via <https://digital.atlas.gov.au/datasets/304f2cc6a8d7443b814569fa8bb3f39e/explore>

```{r setcategories}
categories_to_keep <- c(
  "3.1.0 Plantation forests", "3.3.0 Cropping", "3.3.1 Cereals", "3.3.4 Oilseeds", 
  "3.3.5 Sugar", "3.3.6 Cotton", "3.3.8 Pulses", "3.4.0 Perennial horticulture", 
  "3.4.1 Tree fruits", "3.4.3 Tree nuts", "3.4.5 Shrub berries and fruits", 
  "3.4.8 Citrus", "3.4.9 Grapes", "3.5.4 Seasonal vegetables and herbs",
  
  "4.3.0 Irrigated cropping", "4.3.1 Irrigated cereals", "4.3.4 Irrigated oilseeds",
  "4.3.5 Irrigated sugar", "4.3.6 Irrigated cotton", "4.3.8 Irrigated pulses",
  "4.3.9 Irrigated rice", "4.4.0 Irrigated perennial horticulture", 
  "4.4.1 Irrigated tree fruits", "4.4.2 Irrigated olives", "4.4.3 Irrigated tree nuts",
  "4.4.5 Irrigated shrub berries and fruits", "4.4.8 Irrigated citrus",
  "4.4.9 Irrigated grapes", "4.5.3 Irrigated seasonal vegetables and herbs",
  "4.1.0 Irrigated plantation forests",
  "4.1.2 Irrigated softwood plantation forestry")
```

### Categorise raster information into natural rainfall (or unspecified) agriculture and irrigated agriculture

- Build lookup table from abares_csv (raw ABARES raster at 250m^2^ resolution) to link numeric raster IDs (142) to category name ("3.3.1 Cereals")
- Use lookup table to create a vector of integers on raster values mapped to categories_to_keep
- Reclassify abares_tif to only retain values_to_keep, preserves numeric raster IDs by mapping each value to itself
- Produce clean raster of agricultural cells

```{r categorise, message = FALSE}
level_table <- abares_csv %>%
  dplyr::select(Value, TERTV8) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  arrange(Value) %>%
  mutate(Value = as.integer(Value))

values_to_keep <- level_table$Value[level_table$TERTV8 %in% categories_to_keep]
abares_filtered <- classify(abares_tif, cbind(values_to_keep, values_to_keep), others = NA)
```

### Change resolution to 10 arc-minutes (\~18 km^2^)

- Create a template raster to define the 10 arc-min grid cell size (10/60 degrees) and spatial extent (rough bounding box of Australia)
- Create a function that:
  - Sets projection style in case (WGS84)
  - Converts NA (non-agricultural) cells to 0 before aggregating, otherwise every coarse cell with any agriculture will returns \~1.0 in the next step
  - Groups 250m^2^ cells to 10 arc-minute cells
  - Takes the mean of the 0s (non-agriculture) and 1s (agriculture), i.e. the proportion of agricultural 250m^2^ cells per resampled 10 arc-minute cell
- Apply it to the natural and irrigated rasters

```{r 10arcmin, message = FALSE}
target_res_10 <- rast() # create empty raster
res(target_res_10) <- 10 / 60 # set cell size to 10 arc minutes
ext(target_res_10) <- ext(113, 154, -44, -10) # set to Australia extent

# core function, run identically on each indicator
to_10arcmin_proportion <- function(ind_raster) {
  ind_wgs84  <- project(ind_raster, "EPSG:4326", method = "near") # set projection style
  ind_wgs84  <- ifel(is.na(ind_wgs84), 0L, ind_wgs84) # convert NAs to 0s
  agg_factor <- round((10 / 60) / res(ind_wgs84)[1]) # set aggregation factor
  resample(aggregate(ind_wgs84, fact = agg_factor, fun = "mean", na.rm = FALSE), # mean of each 10 arc-min cell
    target_res_10, method = "near") } # and ensure consistency with the desired output raster

prop_any_ag <- to_10arcmin_proportion(
  ifel(abares_filtered %in% values_to_keep, 1L, NA)) # apply function
```

### Set floor

To avoid including outlying pixels in the final map where only a tiny proportion of the 50 arc minute cell is tagged as agricultural (e.g. one or two of the original 250 m^2^ pixels), set a threshold requirement. This precludes areas outside of the key plant agricultural zone from being included, as they are not representative of the main climate for cropping, horticulture, and forestry.

- Set a threshold at 10%, which is a somewhat arbitrary floor set to include agricultural production down to \~1.8 km^2^ per \~18 km^2^ cell. It sensibly includes areas of coastal Queensland where horticulture and sugarcane industries are present, but excludes the very small horticulture production areas of the Northern Territory
- Cells below the 10% floor threshold become NA, cells above retain their actual proportion value
- Create polygon and save as a vector (shapefile)

```{r threshold, message = FALSE}
floor_thresh <- 0.1 # 10% of a pixel must be agricultural to be included
any_ag_pass  <- ifel(prop_any_ag >= floor_thresh, prop_any_ag, NA)
writeRaster(any_ag_pass, "../data/australia_ag.tif", overwrite = TRUE)
```

### Map the Australian plant agricultural zone

- Reproject to Australian Albers
- Map cells of \>=10% agricultural land on a 10 arc-minute grid to match GirrEO raster information

```{r map setup, message = FALSE}
any_ag_pass <- project(any_ag_pass, "EPSG:3577", method = "near") # set to Australian Albers before mapping

p_combined <- ggplot() +
  geom_spatraster(data = any_ag_pass) +
  geom_spatvector(data = aus_states_albers, fill = NA, colour = "black", linewidth = 0.3) +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colours  = c("#C6E8BC", "#34B8C0", "#80146E"), na.value = NA,
    limits = c(floor_thresh, 1),       # threshold = lower limit allows flexibility in testing
    breaks   = c(floor_thresh, 0.50, 1.0),
    labels   = scales::percent,
    name = "Proportion of plant agricultural land use\n(10 arc-minute or ~324 km² cell size)") +
  labs(title = "Australian plant agricultural zone") +
  theme_void() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.25, size = 10), legend.position = "right")
ggsave("../data/agricultural_density_10arcmin.png", width = 7, height = 6, dpi = 500)
```

